{"key":"processedPost-13960023","value":{"id":13960023,"first":13959463,"last":14348547,"when":1297696796,"utime":"02/14/11 05:19 PM","content":"Fractional sterilization is going to fail with rye more often than it succeeds.&nbsp; I have however, found a better way to sterilize grains without a pressure cooker.<br /><br />First, soak and boil your grains as shown in the <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Grain-Preparation\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">five steps to grain preparation</a>, and then load your hydrated grains into jars with filtered lids.<br /><br />Next, boil/steam them ala brf tek for 8 hours.&nbsp; Don't start counting the 8 hours until steam is escaping from under the lid of your pot.&nbsp; Add small amounts of hot water as necessary during the steaming process to prevent your pot from boiling dry.&nbsp; A second pot used to pre-boil the water really helps here.<br /><br />Once they're done, cool and inoculate.&nbsp; I've had 100% success with this method over the last year in my <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/55-Gallon-Drum-Sterilizer\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">55 gallon drum sterilizer</a> which will sterilize 100 pounds of grain or supplemented sawdust per cycle.<br /><br />I've never much cared for beef cooked in a pressure cooker because it tends to get rubbery and slimy.&nbsp; However, it's the shit for lobster.&nbsp; Cook for five minutes at 5 psi, and then strip the shell off, roll in butter and place on the BBQ grill for a few minutes until the surface of the lobster begins to toast.&nbsp; Damn, makes me want to rob a bank so I can afford a 2 pound rock lobster tail in this economy. <img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/rolleyes.gif\" alt=\":rolleyes:\" title=\":rolleyes:\"/><br />RR<br /><br /><a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/07-009/259775434-Lobster_night_1a.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(